“During LDOC 2018 a bunch of other Black students and I were walking through the crowd going to get water. As we passed a group of white girls one of them reached across me and secretly touched one of my friends hair, turned to her friends and started giggling. I noticed and instantly yelled at her and demanded she apologized to my friend. I don’t remember who she was, I just hope she sees this and that she’s changed.” - Alum ’19

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“My freshman year, I was talking to 2 of my roommate’s white friends. I’m South Indian, and the topic of a Hindu holiday came up. I expressed how my family celebrated it, and I was dismissed by one of these white girls for being wrong because she had an Indian friend back home who did things differently. I told her that India is a huge country and depending on where you from you might do things a bit differently, but I’m sure my past 18 years of experiencing this holiday weren’t “wrong.” At that point, the 2 of them switched the topic entirely. It hurt that a white person felt like they knew more about my culture and experiences than I did and didn’t want to learn.” - Alum ’17

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I was taking Global Mental Health with Professor Puffer. After learning I had mental health and sleep issues, I was struggling to keep up with courses; part of my difficulty was attending classes. I expressed these concerns as she repeatedly spoke of being compassionate to people with mental health issues, understanding the various factors that cause further harm to those with these experienced, and working with individuals to help mitigate exacerbating factors within the class. I also expressed these concerns as it was up to the professor to work with the student and determine the student’s make up exams, assignments, or accommodations. Her response to me: there was nothing she can do and if my class performance didn’t change I would likely fail.” - Alum ’18

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity
This makes me very sad and apprehensive as someone who wants to study mental health. It isn’t an abstract field; practice what you preach is essential to working in mental health

I found this being a similar experience of mine with a psych professor I've had. I find it interesting how the professors that advocate for such and study it are the ones, in my experience, that are very hypocritical and don't practice what they preach when keeping students' mental health a priority

“I am a low income POC who was the only person in years from my high school to go to Duke. My freshman year I got rejected by PWaves. The rejection email said it was a random selection process. When I got to campus a (white) girl casually mentioned that her friend from high school who was a PWaves crew leader told her in summer that she made sure she would get a spot in PWaves. I couldn’t help but notice that 90% of the kids who did PWaves were also wealthy and white, and PWaves is a massive feeder into Greek life. I thought we would all be on equal footing when starting at Duke but seems like these informal networks that wealthy white students have start from the very beginning.” - Alum ’20

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

Or did everyone collectively forget that blatantly racist incident?” - Student ’21

“During freshmen year, my roommate and I were the only Asian girls on our floor. We met all the other girls on our floor, who were predominantly white, during O-Week and during RA floor meetings. They all seemed super nice. However, one night during the first week of school, my roommate walked into the hall bathroom and saw all the girls on our floor doing their makeup and getting ready together. Apparently, there was a frat party that night. Guess which 2 girls on the floor were “accidentally left out” of being invited in their separate GroupMe when they all decided to go together to a frat party.” - Student ’21

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“Freshmen year, a student from my then (white) boyfriend’s old high school came to visit him and tour Duke. She was black and said she wanted to apply ED to Duke. When she left, I went to my boyfriend’s room to talk to him and his roommate (Asian who went to the same high school they did) about how impressive she was and how Duke would be dumb not to take her. I said as an obvious joke, “Oh and she’s black so it’ll be easier for her”. As a black woman, I figured they’d realize I was joking and the absurdity of the statement. But they looked relieved and said “Oh it’s funny you said that, we were just talking about how much easier it’ll be for her!” That moment stuck with me all throughout Duke and even now in grad school. Walking into majority white/non-black or brown academic spaces, I’m hyper aware of the fact most people in that room believe I’m less intelligent than them which causes a lot of anxiety regarding my performance. This is exhausting.” - Alum ’20

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I am an Indian male and during my freshman year I remember going to a KA fraternity party and when I was inside I saw and heard a member point at me and ask who let the Indian guy in. I was completely turned off from going to these type of events ever since.” - Student ’21

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“During debate practice, I was told by a white student that I'm “not black enough” to identify as such. Like others here, I am mixed - Latino, Black, and Asian. She went on to explain that unless I’m at least 50% Black, I can’t identify as such. It was so painful to hear someone who has never experienced life as a minority cast judgment like that.” - Alum ’18

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“In the CulAnth capstone Fieldwork Methods, Professor Wesolowski was telling us how unethical the origins of anthropology had been, and how white men assumed all non-white people were uneducated and incapable of being taught. Later on in that class, we broke up to meet with our project groups. She turned to the Korean girl in my group and said ‘why do you sound like that if your first language is English?’ The Korean girl explained to her that she had a slight speech impediment, and that it wasn’t a foreign accent she was hearing, but instead a lisp.” - Alum

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I was once casually talking to Professor Alex Rosenberg and brought up that my mom grew up in the Bronx since he said was from NYC. He looked at me, and using the information I gave him, immediately assumed that my mom and I were Puerto Rican. Though his assumption was correct, as my mom is Puerto Rican, it was still hurtful and uncomfortable that he made conclusions about my identity based on regional stereotypes and my appearance. He also said something about West Side Story, as if a simplistic and problematic musical could inform him about what my mom’s upbringing was really like.” - Student ’22

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

TW// Suicide

“My roommate and I were friends first semester, but she could not hide her discomfort being in a predominantly Black space or around Black friends of mine she didn’t know. She continuously expressed how “scared” she was of one of my Black friends, and it got to a point where she was “uncomfortable” when my friend wanted to bring her Black boyfriend with us to hang out. She refused to explain why she was so uncomfortable (again, because she was scared of my friend) and when I called her out on not explaining it — specifically saying that I was NOT calling her racist — she accused me of calling her racist, then proceeded to threaten to hurt herself because of our argument. I forgave her, even though she knew I had past experiences of losing friends to suicide and it felt manipulative. She treated me like dirt the next semester (even when I tried to be the bigger person) and ended up moving out unannounced.” - Student ’23

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I’m a South Asian woman, and one time I was in the middle of a conversation with my white guy friend sitting next to me on the C1. We’ve known each other since high school and we’ve always got along. Then, two white girls got on the C1 and he interrupted me in the middle of what I was saying to talk to the two white girls and ignored me for the rest of the bus ride. When we’re alone in person, we click super well. But when other people in Greek life are there, I feel like I don’t exist to him. There are white individuals who are so nice to me one on one, but completely ignore me in group settings.” - Student ’21

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“My Duke in Geneva experience with Martha Reeves and Alex Rosenberg was filled with microagressions. As a Latinx student, I remember feeling very uncomfortable when they would discuss during class and on field trips “running on Spanish time.” They taught it as part of our learning about global business cultures and used it to indirectly criticize Latinx students running late for an outing. They and the class would laugh it off and I didn’t.” - Student ’21

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity
This is ironic and also discriminatory... but I know that in Taiwan we often say people who are slow and often late to live on “American time”. 🤔

“I’ve had too many people reach out to me these past few days because of ICE’s policies to ban international students. My friends tell me “please let us know if we can help” and a few have said “I’ll just marry you so you can stay here.” I’m a US citizen. I was born in America but moved overseas later and live there now. I understand everyone has good intentions, but please don’t make jokes about immigration and finding legal loopholes when there are undocumented immigrants being mass deported in America. And don’t assume I’m an international student when I was born and raised here. Please get to know your friends beyond the surface level.” - Student ’22

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“As an international student I took the class “American dreams - American realities” with Dean Wilson to learn more about history and immigration. I will never forget how small Wilson made me feel. The first day of class he told everyone how the men of my nationality were “better sexual partners” and made me recite my name multiple times because “it sounds so interesting.” Before the final for the class he came over to me and reminded me to “write in English” on my exam. Not to mention the constant jokes and microagressions on my nationality during the entirety of the course.” - Alum ’20

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I went into office hours for STATS101 and when the professor asked for my name (a common western name), her response was “oh that’s one that I can pronounce!”  I’m Chinese American and knowing that many students and faculty in the Statistics department are Chinese, her comment just didn’t sit right.” - Alum ’19

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“One week into my freshman year I was studying for Chem 101 with a group of other students, and we all got to talking about our plans for the future. I told everyone I wanted to be an Orthodontist, and one of the other students told me that I should “rethink that” because “people choose their Orthodontist and no one is going to choose a black woman.”” - Alum ’18

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“In a class, I was told by another black student I am “not black enough” to call myself black. Sure, I’m mixed, but she raised her voice and went on a colorist rant about how she sees a large part of being black as what you look like. She then told another mixed girl in my class, who is hardly darker than me, that she’s black and I am not. College has been a struggle because I don’t fit in anywhere. Black students deny my blackness and I’m not “white enough” to hang out with white students. Who are people to tell me who and what I am?” - Student ’23

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“My mom and I arrived to my freshman dorm room on move-in day feeling ecstatic. We brought a small gift for my roommate and her mom, because in our culture that’s just what you do! The four of us chatted and took photos - I felt it was a lovely start to college. A few days later, my white roommate told me that her mom suggested she request a roommate change, so she could live with someone “a bit more like herself.” But not to worry, she didn’t plan to take this advice. I was speechless, and I couldn’t bear to share this with my mom.” - Alum ’20

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I only took one doc studies class in my time at Duke, and while I enjoyed most of the films we watched, there was one that I felt deserved a strong trigger warning before it was shown. About 30 minutes into the film, we were shown a long series of graphic images from lynchings, without any preparation or warning. We were only told that this was a documentary about Mardi Gras parades. I had a panic attack and didn’t attend my classes for the rest of the day. I wish I had known the other black students in the class, so I could’ve asked if anyone else was affected. But regardless, I feel like we deserved to have some kind of prior knowledge about what we were going to see.” - Alum ’20

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I am an Asian female who was in a sorority for 1 year. During recruitment, the only Asian women in the sorority were paired with almost exclusively Asian rushees, none of whom were ever “top” picks. On bid day, a bunch of white girls started to gather for a photo and I was standing right next to them, and one of them physically pushed me out of the photo. Leaving the group was the best decision I made at Duke.” - Alum ’17

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“During my senior year p-checks, 2 of my friends (both white women) and I were talking to these 2 guys. We went around to introduce our names, and I was told that my South Asian name was too hard to say so it wasn’t worth even trying to remember or learn how to say it. My name is only 3 letters long.” - Alum ’18

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“Sophomore summer I took a globalization class with Alex Rosenberg. He was racist towards all non-white students in the class. He called on us consistently to explain the history of our “ancestors” (I am a second generation Indian-American, so he called on me about India). When I explained that I was born and raised in America and therefore didn’t feel comfortable relaying history I didn’t know well he made fun of me for claiming to be “American”. He later told me I wouldn’t understand the vulgar joke he just told because girls from my culture have a “sheltered upbringing”. I emailed Duke admin about how uncomfortable my whole experience was and never heard any follow up about it.” - Student ’22

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity
What the actual f

“I was sitting in my freshman dormitory common room alone when 3 white/white-presenting guys came in and sat in the couch facing me. This was during O-Week, and there was a meeting for students on financial aid where they give us hoodies and t-shirts for attending. One of the three guys proclaimed loudly, aware that I was in the room, that he will come at the end of this meeting to acquire one of the hoodies. He said that because his parents paid full tuition to Duke, he is more deserving of the hoodie than “those who are not contributing anything” (he said, and I quote). As a someone who is on financial aid, I felt deeply insulted.” - Student ’23

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“During a sociology class taught Deborah Gold, she used the N-Word with a hard r while telling a story. I was stunned that someone so well regarded on campus would use it. I talked to one of my black friends after and we both decided to not confront her, but I still can't shake the feeling of how small she made us feel. White professors always use slurs for shock value while alienating their BIPOC students. It needs to end.” - Alum ’19

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I was hanging out with my white male friend (I’m a black woman) and we were talking about music. He mentioned that only white people liked a certain artist and I told him it wasn’t true because I enjoyed their music. He proceeded to say “exactly” and told me that I’m not “really black”. It was his way of reading my blackness in order for HIM to feel more comfortable being my friend. White people, please stop. You don’t dictate my blackness.” - Student ’22

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I’m Indian, and the summer after my sophomore year I had a “woke” dude (who almost exclusively dated only white women) ask me if I taste “spicy” or “like curry”. Didn’t understand why I couldn’t “take a joke”.“ - Student ’21

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“During my second year at Duke in a small philosophy seminar course, the professor looked at me and told the entire class “this student’s name is an excellent example of implicit bias because many people associate his name with terrorism”. I had never felt more uncomfortable in a course before, and I could just distinctly see everyone staring at me. I just wanted to hide in that moment. I was too afraid to stand up for myself, and I was too afraid to confront my professor for throwing me in the spotlight in front of my peers and using me as an example for a rather negative topic. I felt relieved once I finished that course.” - Student ’21

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I was talking with a friend who is in a different sorority than I am about our sorority rush experiences. She’s a white Latina and I’m black. I told her that her sorority made me feel very uncomfortable and out of place because they were mostly white and blonde. She dismissed my sentiments to talk about how so many people in that sorority are Latina but happen to be white passing. She didn’t seem to understand how or why a mostly white sorority of self proclaimed “nice” girls weren’t welcoming to a black woman.” - Student ’22

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

We want to thank everyone for sharing your stories and making your voice heard on our platform. There are many more we have yet to share because the responses have been overwhelming. Before we move forward we want to make an announcement that will decide the direction of this account.

A week ago, we created this account to hold our peers and leaders accountable. We wanted to follow our peer institutions and give BIPOC a chance to tell their stories in a place where they are marginalized. Regardless of our intentions, we know this account is a distraction if it has not proven to be valuable in actions taken by those in power to make a change.

Please DM us if these stories have led to positive and actionable change in communities that systemically oppress BIPOC, specifically Black, Indigenous, and Latinx folk underrepresented at Duke. If you are white, have these stories led to uncomfortable conversations and concrete actions so that these experiences will be avoided? If you are BIPOC, have you felt supported and heard? If we believe this account hasn’t had the impact we hoped for based on your feedback, we will delete it.

This account was never meant to be entertainment; if you are not working to eradicate racist behavior as a non-BIPOC, then you are abusing and colonizing the experiences and trauma of BIPOC. We will discontinue Dear Duke if that is the case.

“I went to a friend’s party last year and grew more and more worried as the song everyone was singing to got closer to a verse which contained the N-word multiple times. I (Latinx) and the other people in the room (all White) stopped at that verse, but one drunk White girl did not. She SCREAMED that verse, including the N-word multiple times. I was shook, not only at the fact that she did it, but also how no one said anything about it. I didn’t have words. I just left. She’s in Zeta.” - Student ’22

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“Freshman summer, I did a program called Partnership for Appalachian Girls’ Education (PAGE). The program at the time was in partnership with Duke. More specifically, the program director, Deborah Hicks-Rogoff, a white woman, made the program especially uncomfortable, as I was the only Black woman in the area in which we worked. Deborah was informed about a break-in that happened while inhabiting the home we stayed in during the program, neighbors who allowed their dogs to chase me any time I tried to exercise outside, and finally, a head pastor at the local church and his response when I expressed my major as AAAS, “oh, of course, you’re studying that”. Assault and a host of other traumatic events would happen that summer. When my team followed up with Duke, we were taken into a meeting to discuss what happened. We re-hashed our trauma, only to be given a sorry and urged to go about our ways. To this day, Duke and Deborah have done nothing to formally apologize for what we went through. That program took away the meaning of safe spaces for me.” - Alum ’20

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity
As a former PAGE intern, I’m so sorry this happened to you.

As the current PAGE leadership team, we want to acknowledge that we’ve seen this post, are processing it, and are deeply troubled by it. Most importantly, we are so sorry that this student felt unwelcome and unsafe while working with PAGE and that they’re burdened with residual trauma because of it. We are committed to learning from this experience and attempting to repair harm where possible. We intend to reach out to this student directly, not to demand further action or recall, but to let them know we hear them, we’re taking their testimony seriously, and have taken steps in the years since to better support students of color and to center Black and non-black POC Appalachian voices and experiences in our work. As an organization, we learned from and are still learning from summer 2017. This post serves an important reminder that there is more internal work to do. We are committed to doing it, and to sharing it. Our other alumni can expect to hear from us, too, in case there are other things they want to share, and to learn about our previous and future action steps to ensure that we’re upholding our values to be an antiracist organization in Appalachia. We appreciate the BIPOC students who are using this platform to hold Duke, and its people and programs, accountable for racial injustice.
@cj.mirabile didn’t you do this program?!

@tayjay_ Yes. This same summer. I can attest that this account only captures a glimpse of what that summer was like. With a powerful mission lead program, you would think volunteers would be treated better. While we tried to amplify the voices of students, ours were continuously silenced.

“When I was taking SOCIOL332 with Prof. Jenifer Hamil-Luker, she made us act as Black and gay people and sex workers in order to do “interactive” learning about unethical experiments like the Tuskegee syphilis experiment, Humphrey’s tearoom trade, Operation Midnight Climax, and the Stanford Prison Experiment. In a class of mostly white students, no one found any problems with this, and in fact, Hamil-Luker is widely beloved by these white students.” - Student ’22

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity
is there some way stories like this (especially with specific profs) can be brought to the attention of either the prof or their department to help prevent this from happening?

“As a junior, I was having trouble getting an internship/job to meet the global health major’s experience learning requirement. I met with my Global Health advisor to ask for resources and if she knew of any other internships or programs I could apply for. She was extremely unhelpful and when I started panicking because I kept getting rejected and was worried I wouldn’t be able to meet this requirement without the department’s help, she “advised” me to drop my major to a minor, because “that would still be a huge accomplishment for someone like you”. She didn’t explicitly say that it was because I am a Hispanic woman, but I know that she would never have given that advice to a white student. She didn’t end up actually helping me until I escalated the situation to the department chair and told them about her “advice”.” - Alum ’22

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“Victor Strandberg is one of the highest-rated Professors at Duke and, as someone considering an English major, I was constantly told by (white) students that he was “legendary”. So, I took his class spring semester. He read  the n word (hard r) out loud multiple times and also used it in lecture. Not to mention these books that featured the n word, which he called some of the “best books ever written”, were written by white authors. He also had a single word that he used to describe every culture and (being Latinx myself) I was very uncomfortable when he explained that the one word he used to describe Latinx culture as a whole was “machismo”. I will never EVER understand what can be “legendary” about a man who uses racial slurs in class and uses generalizations/stereotypes to describe an entire culture.” - Student ’23

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I am an Asian American woman. In class the day before Thanksgiving break, my professor looked around the nearly empty classroom and said, “Look whose homes are too far to leave for break.” I was in fact flying back home to California the next day, which I stated. Some time after that, I went to his office hours to ask a question, and when I didn’t get something, he explained that “we do things differently in the US.” I was baffled as to how it’s so hard to understand that this is my home too, and I was angry that he wasn’t listening.” - Grad Student ’22

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“Freshman year, I was hanging out with a white man, another Hispanic woman, an Asian woman, and an Asian guy. The white man asked me what my ethnicity was and, assuming I was among friends, I told him I was Mexican. He immediately sat up straight and said “OH! Well that’s why you’re here.” I was shocked that he felt like he could speak that way to me, especially since I had assumed he was normal because he had a diverse friend group. Clearly it doesn’t matter though — performative wokeness is rampant on this campus. I stayed silent then (freshman year), so the other Hispanic woman in the room stood up for me. I am so grateful for her strength in using her voice — that interaction taught me a lot about standing up for others. It took me until senior year to confront this white male friend about how the incident made me feel. When I did, he told me that the fact I even brought it up made HIM feel bad and ruined HIS day. He’s since apologized for the original comment and his reaction senior year — but only after asking his diverse friends to do the emotional work of educating him AND reaching out to me on his behalf. This is the part that really irritates me: why do white students make everything about them?” - Alum ’20

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“In my freshman year Engineering Design class, I experienced subtle discrimination because as the only black man in the class, 100% of the times my suggestions were shot down in my mostly white project teams. What hurt the most was when someone would repeat my suggestions later on and they would be listened to and accepted as “good ideas”. I still see this going on 3 years down the line.” - Student ’21

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“During my first week at Duke, I walked into the Giles common room looking to meet new people. I sat on the couch and listened to what everyone was talking about. One white male got up and yelled “Why do I hate Obama? Because he’s a fucking Muslim. Fuck that guy.” As a Muslim student, this was my first experience with hate at Duke.” - Alum ’20

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“During my years at Duke, the Yik Yak app was very popular. One time, my white male friend was laughing at a highly-liked comment on the app. When I asked him what he was laughing about, he said, “Oh, you’d probably be offended.” When I pressed, he showed me the comment with the location being Perkins Library: “It’s great that you speak Chinese put please shut the fuck up.”” - Alum ’16

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I’m an RA, and one night I was woken up at around 3 am to handle a noise complaint down the hall. When I knocked on the door, a white boy (not the resident of the room) answered and asked me why I was there. I told him that I was the RA of the hall and asked to speak to the resident who lived in that room. He responded by looking me up and down, shutting the door on me, and yelling to his friend that “some black girl” was at the door, even after I had told him that I was the RA. I felt so blatantly disrespected, and it reiterated the notion that no matter what position I hold or what accolades I achieve, some people will never see me for more than my skin color.” - Student ’22

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“A professor (who has since retired) gave me my friend’s final grade instead of my own and didn’t realize until we both emailed him. We were the only two Asian women in the class, a 10 person seminar, and we look nothing alike. I made an effort to speak up during discussions and thought I had a pretty good relationship with that professor, so when he mistook me for a totally different person after a whole semester, it stung.” - Alum ’19

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“During my junior year, I was in a statistics class. For lab we were put into groups, and I was paired with two white men. I found that whenever I expressed my thoughts while working on group assignments, I was often ignored. During a lab, I had an answer to a question on our problem set and one of my white group members told me I was wrong. He assumed I didn’t know what I was talking about. He proceeded to ask the TA who confirmed my answer. He didn’t acknowledge the fact that I had already said the correct answer. This happened multiple times throughout the semester. As a black woman, working in group projects can sometimes make you feel small and unimportant. It’s difficult to get people to listen to you when they don’t believe you should be at Duke in the first place.” - Alum ’20

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“I went to a professor (who scorned my emails at first) to say I’d like to study pharmacology. She told me “people like me” don’t usually do well in pharmacology.” - Staff

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“Being Black at Duke: I walked in the Edge to meet up with a friend. After seeing no other available chairs at his table, I asked a neighboring table, with all Asian students, if I could use one of their empty seats. When I asked politely, one of the students angrily shooed me away and said under his breath, “Just take it and leave,” as if I was a second-class citizen in the space. I was in shock, but quickly let it go (as I often have to do here). Even my non-Black friend voiced his concern over what just happened. As a Black person at Duke stepping into and merely existing in predominantly white and Asian spaces, I’ve had numerous experiences like this, some when I was tokenized, or some when people straight up stared at me. To my white and Asian peers: I am not your diversity enrollment or your handout. Being Black and academically high achieving or intelligent are not mutually exclusive. We deserve to be here whether you like it or not. PERIOD.” - Alum ’20

#dearduke #duke #dukeuniversity

“Last year, Duke celebrated the 50th anniversary of the Allen Building Takeover where Duke’s first Black students post-desegregation launched a protest in 1969 to bring attention to issues of racism plaguing the University. A bunch of alumni from that event were invited to Duke to give their perspective and memories. One of the alumni, now a retired physician, from that event told us about how during the protest, Dean Gerald Wilson came up to him angrily and told him that he would personally write to every medical school he had applied to dissuade them from admitting him. According to him, every medical school denied him, except one medical school at an HBCU. He came back a few years later after graduating from medical school and confronted Dean Wilson over this. Hearing this story really sent chills down my spine as a POC Duke student. I always considered Dean Wilson to be this benign elderly, tolerant white guy, always happy to share his liberal perspectives in his legendary “American Dreams, American Realities” course. Makes you really wonder who else at the University has went out of their way to punish individuals who question the status quo.” - Alum ’19

“Senior spring, I was writing my honors thesis for GSF and taking a GSF capstone course. For the course, our final project was to submit a chapter of our thesis. This was an odd idea on her part, since our class professor had never advised a thesis before and was NOT our advisor anyway. Long story short, she read my work and told me that, “it’s obvious you don’t know how to do research. You should have turned this into your thesis advisor earlier so they could tell you not to waste your time. Are you sure you want to go to grad school? What a shame.” I cried afterwards and felt absolutely disheartened (I’m a first-gen, low-income, Afro-Latinx woman) and I wasn’t the only woman of color she did this to. I got the last laugh, though, because I got “high distinction” and was admitted to an Ivy-League PhD program with said project.” - Alum ’19

“I am a mixed race woman; my mom is from the Caribbean and my dad is white. My freshman year during O-week, I was at a pregame with white girls I had met in a preorientation program and the age-old “what are you” question came up. In the conversation, one of the girls told me that I “was exotic, but still pretty.” Between the word “exotic” (which should only be used to describe plants, spices, etc.) and the “but” qualifier (a subtle way of establishing non-“exotic”/whiteness as the standard for pretty), I felt so uncomfortable my first week on campus. I still feel insecure about my ethnic ambiguity, and comments like these don’t help.”

“I loved being a part of Hoof ‘n’ Horn in undergrad, and I love that the org is doing a lot of work to increase its inclusion of students and narratives of color in its productions, but I don’t know if I’ll ever entirely get over how difficult and painful it was to fight to get shows like In the Heights and The Wiz to be considered. My freshman year, I was told we could never do a show that featured narratives of color because the students of color within the org, myself included, and those outside of the HnH community didn’t have the talent to carry a whole show on our own. It’s amazing to me that the same people who said those words can so loudly celebrate the progress that’s been made without acknowledging the actions they took to minimize the value of actors and creators of color in theatrical spaces.” - Alum ’20
